text:
Dear Bajaj Chetak Electric Team,

I am writing to express my serious concern and disappointment regarding my experience with the Bajaj Chetak Electric scooter that I purchased from PL bajaj (Jaipur) on 31st March 2025.

Despite it being a premium electric scooter, I have faced several unexpected issues in just three months of ownership:

Basic parts like the lady footrest and main stand were not included with the scooter. When I inquired at the showroom, I was told I would need to pay ‚Çπ1500 for the footrest and ‚Çπ300 for installation, which I feel is unfair for such essential parts.

Within three months of usage, I was informed that the disc pads had worn out and had to pay ‚Çπ700+ to replace them. It is surprising that brake pads need replacement so soon in a new vehicle.

The most serious issue is the drastic drop in battery performance. Initially, the scooter gave me a range of around 120 km per charge, but now it barely covers 32 km per charge. When I reported this to the showroom, they informed me that the battery is faulty and would take around one month to be replaced.

My question is: How is a working person expected to manage for one full month without a vehicle? People buy electric vehicles to save money and reduce fuel dependency, but this experience has created the opposite effect.

We first pay extra for essential accessories. Then, within just three months, the battery fails. Now, I‚Äôm being asked to wait a full month for resolution. At this rate, using a petrol bike would be more practical and reliable.

There is no assurance that the same issue won‚Äôt happen again after the battery is replaced. So does this mean that even with a battery warranty of 50,000 km or 3 years, I will need to leave the vehicle at the service center for 1 month every 3-4 months? And once the warranty ends, I‚Äôll be forced to spend ‚Çπ40,000‚Äì‚Çπ50,000 for a new battery?

If this is the reality, then what is the point of owning an electric vehicle?

To add to this, this issue hasn‚Äôt occurred with me alone. One of my friends also bought the same model from the same showroom on the same day ‚Äî and is facing the exact same battery issue. Both of our scooters are now lying in the showroom for battery replacement.

Therefore, I request the following from your team:

Provide a temporary alternative vehicle or support during this long battery replacement period.

Share a clear explanation and written assurance that such issues won‚Äôt repeat frequently.

Offer a form of compensation or support for the inconvenience and recurring expenses.

If I do not receive a proper response or resolution, I will be forced to share my detailed 3‚Äì4 month experience across online platforms, YouTube reviewers, and with my media contacts at Rajasthan Patrika ‚Äî not to defame, but to inform other customers about potential issues they may face.

Please understand this is not just about one complaint, but a matter of trust that is being lost.
